value.value: Decreased concentration of fibrinogen in the blood.
Anomaly in the level or the function of hemoglobin, the oxygen-carrying protein of erythrocytes.

Hemoglobin F (HbF) contains two globin alpha chains and two globin gamma chains. It is the main form of hemoglobin in the fetus during the last seven months of intrauterine development and in the half year of postnatal life. In adults it normally makes up less than one percent of all hemoglobin. This term refers to an increase in HbF above this limit. In beta thalassemia major, it may represent over 90 percent of all hemoglobin, and in beta thalassemia minor it may make up between 0.5 to 4 percent.
A reduction in the ratio of production of beta globin to that of alpha globin. This is the major abnormality in the various forms of beta thalassemia.
Excessive, increased hair growth located in the lumbar region.
Bending or curvature of a fourth toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).

label.value: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex I

value.value: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex I, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

label.value: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex III

value.value: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex III, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.
Inflammation of the bronchioles.
Impaired ability to eat related to problems gathering food and getting ready to suck, chew, or swallow it.
Replacement of bone marrow by fibrous tissue.

A bulging of the interatrial septum towards one side. In adults, atrial septal aneurysm can be defined as a protrusion of the aneurysm of >10 mm beyond the plane of the atrial septum as measured by transesophageal echocardiography.

definition.value: Atrial septal aneurysm formation may be secondary to raised interatrial pressure gradients, producing a bulging septal shift toward the low-pressure side. However, it has been also found in patients with normal atrial pressures, suggesting a primary (congenital) malformation.

value.value: The feeling and belief that one is being targeted or is a focus of negative or untoward actions, overt or covert, from others. The affected individual expresses a concern that people are in general against the individual and are engaging in subtle behaviors to make things difficult for them. The origins of such thinking may arise from real events and become amplified over time. Paranoia may also arise in the absence of any action or interaction between the person and their environment.

definition.value: Paranoia is defined as a non-delusional state characterized by a vague sense that 'everyone and anyone' is unfavorable towards one as in 'the whole world hates me'. A persecutory delusion is, in contrast, typically fixed and focused - as in 'my neighbor is pumping poison into my house'.

value.value: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the temporal region.
A type of asthma in which aspirin and other nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) that inhibit cyclooxygen-ase 1 (COX-1) exacerbate bronchoconstriction.
A reduced concentration of calcitriol in the blood. Calcitriol is also known as 1,25-dihydroxycholecalciferol or 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3.

definition.value: A personality disorder is a deeply ingrained pattern of behavior of a specified kind that deviates markedly from the norms of generally accepted behavior. It is typically apparent by the time of adolescence and causes long-term difficulties in personal relationships or functioning in society.

A personality disorder is generally associated with significant problems and limitations in relationships, social encounters, work, and school. It usually manifests since childhood or adolescence and continues throughout adulthood.

A personality disorder characterized by impulsive behavior and unpredictable, capricious mood. Affected individuals show a tendency to have outbursts of emotion and an inability to control these behavioral explosions. They generally experience an intense fear of abandonment or instability and also struggle with feelings of emptiness.

value.value: An abnormal color of the urine, that is, the color of the urine appears different from the usual straw-yellow color.

label.value: Edema of the dorsum of feet

value.value: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin on the back of the feet.

An anomaly of the mitochondrion, the membranous cytoplasmic organelle the interior of which is subdivided by cristae. The mitochondrion is a self replicating organelle that is the site of tissue respiration.
Inflammation of the liver.
A phenomenon in which persons repetitively pull out their own hair, resulting in noticeable hair loss.
Habitual biting of one's own body.

definition.value: Biting of one's own arms, lip, check, finger etc.

value.value: Concentration of protoporphyrins in erythrocytes above the upper limit of normal.
Transient episodes of weakness of the arm, leg, and in some cases the face on one side of the body.
A type of headache characterized by repeated attacks of unilateral pain lasting 15 to 180 minutes and associated with local autonomic signs.

definition.value: According to the International Classification of Headache Disorders (ICHD-II), the diagnosis of cluster headache can be made with at least five attacks fulfilling criteria B-D: (B) Severe or very severe unilateral orbital, supraorbital and/or temporal pain lasting 15-180 minutes if untreated. (C) Headache is accompanied by at least 1 of the following: (i) Ipsilateral conjunctival injection and/or lacrimation. (ii) Ipsilateral nasal congestion and/or rhinorrhea. (iii) Ipsilateral eyelid edema. (iv) Ipsilateral forehead and facial sweating. (v) Ipsilateral miosis and/or ptosis. (vi) A sense of restlessness or agitation. (D) Attacks have a frequency from 1 every other day to 8/day. Additionally, the headaches cannot attributed to another disorder.

value.value: Any structural anomaly of the acrosome resulting in a round sperm head.
An abnormal reduction in the mobility of ejaculated sperm.
Any structural anomaly of the kidney.
An abnormal functionality of the kidney.
An erythematous eruption commonly associated with drug reactions or infection and characterized by inflammatory nodules that are usually tender, multiple, and bilateral.

definition.value: The nodules of erythema nodosum are located predominantly on the shins with less common occurrence on the thighs and forearms. They undergo characteristic color changes ending in temporary bruise-like areas, and usually subside in 3-6 weeks without scarring or atrophy.

value.value: Narrowing of the urethra associated with inflammation or scar tissue.

definition.value: A urethral stricture may result from surgery, disease, or injury. The term should not be used for a congenital narrowing of the urethra (Consider the term Urethral stenosis, HP:0008661).

value.value: A type of headache that last hours with continuous pain of mild or moderate intensity, bilateral location, a pressing/tightening (non-pulsating) quality and that is not aggravated by routine physical activity such as walking or climbing stairs.
Decreased time between the start of the Q wave and the end of the T wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).
Marked decrease in the number of granulocytes.

definition.value: Agranulocytosis is defined as an absolute neutrophil count less than 500 cells/microliter.

value.value: A type of agranulocytosis related to ingestion of a specific medication.
Anomaly of primary or secondary sexual development or characteristics.
Increased time for the PR interval (beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the QRS complex).

definition.value: In adults, normal values are 120 to 200 ms long.

label.value: Dynein arm defect of respiratory motile cilia

value.value: An anomaly of the dynein arms of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.

definition.value: The peripheral microtubules in the canonical 9 + 2 microtubular pattern of motile cilia are studded with dynein arms that contain adenosine triphosphatases and act as molecular motors to effect the sliding of the peripheral microtubular pairs relative to one another.

label.value: Absent inner and outer dynein arms

value.value: Complete absence of the dynein arms of respiratory motile cilia, that is, absence of the inner and the outer dynein arms, which normally are situated inside and outside of the peripheral microtubules of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.

Any anomaly of the normal motility of motile cilia. Evaluation of ciliary beat frequency and ciliary beat pattern requires high-speed videomicroscopy of freshly obtained ciliary biopsies that are maintained in culture media under controlled conditions.

definition.value: Ciliated epithelial cells bear approximately 200 motile (9 + 2) cilia that move with both intracellular and intercellular synchrony. The pattern of beat in 9 + 2 motile cilia occurs in a waveform having a forward effective stroke followed by a return stroke. The direction of stroke is a function of the directional orientation of the central microtubules. In addition to moving in synchrony, individual cilia in normal cells are very plastic and move fluidly, sometimes deforming briefly upon encountering resistance and/or particles being transported over the mucosal surface. Cilia are embedded in a watery periciliary fluid of low viscosity, which facilitates the rapid beat cycle to move the more viscous overlying layer of mucus. Ciliary beat frequency ranges from approximately 8-20 Hz under normal conditions but may be accelerated by exposure to irritants such as tobacco smoke.

value.value: Inflammation of the flexor digitorum tendon, often associated with the Kanavel signs: (i) finger held in slight flexion, (ii) fusiform swelling, (iii) tenderness along the flexor tendon sheath, and (iv) pain with passive extension of the digit.

definition.value: Tenosynovitis refers to inflammation of the protective sheath that surrounds a tendon. Stenosing tenosynovitis, or trigger finger, is diagnosed when a patient presents with a symptomatic locking or clicking of a finger or the thumb. It is caused by a mismatch between the volume of the flexor tendon sheath and its contents. As the flexor tendon attempts to glide through a relatively stenotic sheath, it catches, producing an inability to flex or extend the digit smoothly.

value.value: Any deviation from the normal concentration of serine in the blood circulation.
Abnormality of the occipital bone of the skull.
Underdevelopment of the arch of aorta.
Inflammation of the sacroiliac joint, generally accompanied by lower back pain.
Myoclonus that occurs during the initial phases of sleep.
An odontogenic tumor of the cementum of tooth.
A functional abnormality of the autonomic nervous system.
